ressed its many 'alternative' -non-ecclesiastical in the broadest sense - manifestations. The authors aim to open up a relatively unexplored and often quite hidden dimension of religion in the modern world through non-confessional, critical study. They establish both the vibrancy of contemporary experiments in alternative spirituality, as well as its historical pedigree. The broad range of subject matter includes magical ritual, independent seekers and gurus, the Theosophical movement, C. G. Jung, turn-of-the-century artistic and spiritual colonies, Iona and Glastonbury, alternative healing, and the influence of secular and humanistic thought. Readers of this fascinating book will gain an overall sense of the sociological, anthropological, historical and ethnographical perspectives on the study of religion and the many alternative forms of spirituality.Key FeaturesInternational names contributing to this subject areaIncreasingly important subject in courses in Religious Studies and SociologyWide range of voices in contributions  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aBeckford, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowman, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBowman, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruce, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenwood, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHedges, Ellie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.